The paper deals with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and proposes a new procedure called "network deconvolution" to optimize the training process. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the structure of the first layer of the network resembling biological neurons in the visual regions of the brain, which suggests a possible connection to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of sparse representation, which is a topic commonly studied in the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper applies the proposed method to various datasets, including image classification tasks, which suggests a possible connection to the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category.
